column18:
Forecasting is a technique that uses historical data as inputs to make informed estimates that are predictive that helps the company gear up to meet future demands. It is a vital tool in operations management such that it impacts all business functions and operations decisions. Forecasting is mostly used  in predictive analytics.

Forecasts are rarely perfect and forecasting involves uncertainty. It may be hard perfect but the goal is to keep forecast errors as low as possible to arrive at close to perfect figures. Forecasts are more accurate for shorter than longer time horizons. Shorter time horizon may mean a lower degree of uncertainty because data variations are minimal for data with short coverage.

column18: I like best in the course is the use of Time Series Forecasting. Time series forecasting means to forecast or to predict the future value over a period of time. It entails developing models based on previous data and applying them to make observations and guide future strategic decisions. It?s not always an exact prediction, and likelihood of forecasts can vary wildly?especially when dealing with the commonly fluctuating variables in time series data as well as factors outside our control. With the insights gained  from forecasted data, we may be able to use them to make observations and drive future strategic decision-making to be able to achieve organizations goals.

column18:
Project Charter is a formal, typically short document that describes the project in its entirety.
The documentation includes what the objectives are, how it will be carried out, and who the stakeholders are. A Project charter was created once a business case is approved and it is usually draws from the business case for the financial parameters in which the project needs to operate.

column19:
To be honest, I would prefer to do this evaluation at the actual end of the course because I feel like I would have better feedback after doing the final exam or capstone. 

These happened to completely different courses but I feel like it applies to any course.

An example is, avoid using screenshots when asking students to compute something in excel, just give them a spreadsheet, not let them encode it all manually. Less prone to errors that way. (this was observed in a final exam). 

Or if the course lacks graded evaluations and has the final capstone as their only form of official evaluation, maybe not make it something so subjective as peer evaluation and lean towards a more objective way of evaluation.

column18:
In week 1, I learned that Public Financial Management (PFM) is important in supporting macroeconomic stability, economic growth, and the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDG). It is important in managing public finances of the economy. PFM encompasses the seven areas budgeting, accounting, auditing, revenue generation, cash management, debt management and public reporting on public sector financial operations. The elements of Good and Effective budgeting are; Aggregate fiscal discipline or spending within means, it is controlling the level of spending. Allocative efficiency or spending on the right priorities, it is spending on the right things and setting priorities straight. Technical efficiency or spending with measurable results, is spending at the right cost and producing more with less cost. Budget Preparation input requires budget call and budget priorities, the process are formulation of FEs, citizen engagement, program convergence budgeting, tier 2 agency proposal, budget hearings and review, presentation to the president and consolidation, validation, confirmation. The output should be the President's Budget. Budget Legislation input requires the President's budget. The process are home deliberations, senate deliberations, bicameral deliberations, ratification and enrolment, and enactment. The output of this is the General Appropriations Acts (GAA) or the People's budget. Budget execution includes, early procurement activities, budget programming, allotment release, obligation, issuance of notice of cash allocation and disbursement. The implementation are being monitored and evaluated during budget accountability. It includes performance targets, accountability reports, public disclosures, performance review, publication of mid-year and year-end reports and audit.

In week 2, I learned that budget allocations are further classified as to sector, expense class, regions, recipient unit, special purpose funds, and appropriation source. The allocation of the national government budget for major sector includes social services, economic services, general public services, debt burden and defense. Budget dimensions by expense class includes Personnel services(PS), maintenance and other operating expenses (MOOE), capital outlays (CO), and financial expenditures (FinEx). I also learned that budget can also be classified according to the appropriation source.

In week 3, I learned about the sources of the government?s revenues ? tax and non-tax revenues. The major classes of tax revenue are taxes on income and profits, taxes on property, taxes on domestic goods and services, taxes on international trade and transactions and other sources. Non tax revenues are Bureau of the treasury (BTr) income, privatization, fees and charges, and other sources. Other sources of revenue are income tax, estate and donor's taxes, value added tax, other percentage taxes, excise taxes, documentary stamp taxes and other taxes. Reforming the tax system is important for it promotes investment, create jobs and reduce poverty. Some features of the CTRP are TRAIN Law, tax amnesty, sin taxes. 
 
In week 4, I learned the importance of government borrowings and debt service. Government borrows money to spend on the welfare of their people, to   support services programs and projects. Especially when the country facing a challenge like this pandemic, it is important to meet the needs of the people for their safety and security. To finance national government deficits, to obtain foreign exchange, to secure financing at more favorable terms than the opportunity cost of revenues, to take advantage of benefits attached to the funds and to balance the timing of resources with the project gestation and repayment of benefit.

"The bridging of digital and physical environments, the convergence of Information Technology and Operational Technology, and all the new technologies such as the Internet of Things, Big Data, Cloud with additional accelerators such as advanced robotics and Artificial Intelligence, have enabled the Fourth Industrial Revolution." 

Enabling the fourth Industrial Revolution, people lives much be easier with Artificial intelligence and robotics are rapidly increasing the jobs that machines can perform better and faster than people. While this may reduce costs and raise productivity, it will also threaten jobs, particularly low-skilled, repetitive jobs (such as assembly line workers).

column18:
I liked best in the course is that it teaches us that citizen and government should work hand in hand to be able to have a livable city as such, G2C e-services can be categorized in terms of the degree of interaction between the government and the citizens through information, consultation and participation. To provide information to the citizens, Government websites with information on policies and programs, laws and regulations, budgets, and other issues of public interest. This aims to quickly and easily provide access to information and services to individuals. 
Consultation. This is where the Governments offer online consultation mechanism and tools, which present citizens with choices about public policy topics and encouragement to contribute. This helps the government to improve its  citizen-centered decision and policy-making.
Participation. This intends the Government to incorporate citizens into decision-making processes, generally through participatory budgeting. They provide online participation platforms where citizens can propose, discuss, give feedback, and vote for initiatives aimed to solve or improve a wide range of situations and problems in different aspects of a city.

column19:
Personally, I love to learn and I value this opportunity given to us. I have finished five courses here in Project SPARTA and I am very thankful for all the hard work of your team. Unfortunately, this course has a lot of issues. 

First, the lecture videos are lacking in detail. If the audience are expected to be beginners in data science, the speed and depth in which the topics will be handled should consider this. The lecture videos jump from topic to topic without a clear discussion of the lesson. Steps were quickly listed without any step-by-step guidance. Considering that we are learning a new service (i.e. GCP), the material should?ve been more friendly to those without a background on this. Even if you carefully follow the provided steps, it would lead to an error in GCP because of the lack of clarity in the lecture video. Although one might argue that we should do our own self-study outside of the course, the counterargument is that there should be at least some guidance on extra resources or a screen recording on how to do it. For example, my experience in SP201 and SP401 was helpful since I was shown either a screen recording of how to do the excel functions or a Youtube video on how to do the corporate dashboard report. With a complex service such as GCP, it is more so expected that the course will have a detailed guide. 

Second, the assessment had problems with validity. Besides the problems with the answer key, it wasn?t helpful in assessing the learning objectives. In my other courses (e.g. SP201, SP401, SP501), the assessment really tested our skills through a task that prompted us to apply our learning. I really appreciated those assignments, despite the difficulty, because I knew that I was really honing a skill that I can bring back to my work and research. Unfortunately, in this case, it appears that the assessment was given for the sake of having an assessment. 

Lastly, I noticed that the content of the video and the assessment needs updating. Comparing the GCP content in the video and the current GCP content on the web, there are differences that should also be reflected in the assessment. 
I am interested in learning about data science. I spend my weekends studying and doing my tasks because I see value in this government initiative. Unfortunately, one can?t help but be saddened if the potential of the course is wasted on poorly prepared materials.

As the second course in the pathway, the dicussion and especially the module 4 exit assessment is way too advanced. I don't know if it was intentional but I'm quite certain that nobody expects to immediately dive into code in their second course in. I can't help to think that the course was a missed opportunity. Instead of learners appreciating the powers of GCP and cloud computing, most were blindsided with the complexity and technicality and thrown into confusion.

Perhaps a way to enhance the delivery was to leave out the technical side and codes, or lessen them if inevitable, and center the dicussion on the process of building data products and where do the numerous tools come into play by providing simple, real world applications.

A real-time assistant could also help answer concerns, problems, and issues, such as when learners get stumped in the middle of an activity or have questions about the quizzes.

Showing the correct answers, perhaps, right after the quiz could help learners remember the right answers right there and then and learn what they're supposed to learn; instead, of waiting for email replies when one has already jumped to new lessons, in the process, forgetting what should be remembered.

column19:
Please dedicate more time and material to contextualising the formulas and functions. Rather than just showing students how to format these correctly, present more examples / use cases, as well as (when applicable) how to interpret formula/function results correctly.

For example, the section on statistical functions presents information on functions like STDEV and VAR. But some students may be coming into the course with no knowledge of when it's appropriate to use these functions, as well as what the resulting values from these functions might mean.

The course's focus on the mechanics of using Excel also isn't particularly beneficial for students who may already be familiar with Excel. The course materials hinge too much on particulars of layout (e.g., instructions to click on particular icons in a section of the command ribbon), which may be tedious for students who are already coming in with knowledge of certain keyboard shortcuts, for example. This kind of particularity also isn't always helpful for beginners, as layout details, etc. may differ across different versions of Excel, leading to confusion for beginners who may not have exactly the same layout as what's described in the course (e.g., Mac users, or those with older versions of Excel).

All in all, the course could be enhanced in two major ways:
1. Adding more context to the tools being taught, so that students learn not just how to use these but when, why, and how best to do so.
2. Rethinking the presentation of the course or finding a way to calibrate the material better to serve varying skill levels. (Some options to consider would be: allowing intermediate students to skip earlier sections after passing some kind of assessment; retooling the module quizzes to not depend so heavily on little details that may not be the same across different versions of Excel; etc.)

column19:
1. Review and improve the gamified exercises (Let's Recall). Although the exit assessment questions  are well-made, the exercise questions are bad. The exercise questions seem to have been randomly picked from the course materials, leaving behind the context. The exercises (Let's Recall) are hard to answer because the context is left out. Compare this with the assessment questions that properly lays down the context of the question.

2. Use the laser pointer when showing a slide with lots of information. Many of the slides are rich in information. The down-side to this is that when the speaker starts talking about a part of the slide, the listener can easily get lost trying to find the item the speaker is talking about. This can be remedied by using the laser pointer feature in PPT or Google Slides.

column18: New knowledge that I was able to gain from this live session were the basics of SQL Basic function like retrieving all data or a specific column/s in a data sets as well as giving conditions to your query. I also learned how to aggregates data like getting the sum and average of a certain columns (numerical), getting the min and max values, grouping by specific columns, etc. And lastly, I also learned how to join two data sets without uploading a new merged data. JOIN clause is used to combine rows from two or more tables, based on a related column between them.

column18: Data Management is new to me and I have learned how it is practically important in any organization. I am a teacher and my school has recently implemented a plan on how to manage and protect the school's data collection. Based on the series of discussion with all the members of the school, they have come up with a plan and series of processes on paper about how to handle school data. And as anybody's guess, it was the IT section of the school that was chosen to head the data management plan. From what I remember about the open consultation, the head and even the upper school management have really no robust idea of what data management is and how to go about it. I believe they were just trying to come up with a data management plan because the Data Privacy Act and Anti-Cyber Crime Law demands it. I can only think of a host of problems and issues arising from this scenario. Hopefully, my knowledge from this course and the subsequent courses about data management in SPARTA would allow me shed some light and provide significant help on this matter. Because, learning and finishing the course is already rewarding overall.

column18: The lesson games part?

Data management is a difficult task. Data is managed in many locations inside an organization by teams responsible for different aspects of the data lifecycle. Design skills are required to plan systems, highly technical skills to administer hardware and build software, data analysis skills to understand issues and problems, analytic skills to interpret data, language skills to bring consensus to definitions and models, and strategic thinking to see opportunities to serve customers and meet goals. The problem is getting people with such a diverse set of talents and viewpoints to realize how the parts fit together so that they can work well together to achieve common goals.

I liked the exercises best because they are gamified, with multiple trials and took on different types of games or puzzles. Although the leaderboard was a turn off since they're mostly fakes registering impossible scores! 

The most rewarding parts are the lessons that list  the scope, rules, requirements, tools, and metrics since they're very informative and came as lists?although only from my Notes because even the lists are in lecture form, which are harder to digest and visualize.
column19:
More presentations to digest the longish lectures, that led me to simply reading the transcript instead of listening and taking down notes at the same time to understand what's being said. 

Topic is theoretical and, therefore, difficult. 

PPTs, tables, graphs, and other visual aids should make the lecture lighter to avoid the monotony of lists and discussions, making them more memorable.

The End Quizzes are also not working in a way because almost all items include None of the Above and tend to be confusing. To reinforce learning, the correct answers should be the ones highlighted, the questions need to be formulated positively, and perhaps not as lists requiring multiple answers. 

The True or False questions are better in driving home the point.

column18:
As an RF Optimization engineer were statistical data are the bread and butter of our daily task and data that are mostly considered in analysis to improve our network performance are statistical data gathered in our system which only considers the sites performance. To able to give our subscribers the best network performance we should also considered crowdsourcing data. Crowdsourcing is the collection of information, opinions, or work from a group of people, usually sourced via the Internet. Crowdsourcing work allows companies to save time and money while tapping into people with different skills or thoughts from all over the world. 
Crowdsourcing data is an effective way to seek the help of a large audience usually through the internet to gather information on how to solve the company's problems, generate new ideas and innovations.
With this, optimizing our network would be more subscriber-centered rather than system (site) performance.

column18: None. In fact, this course is the worst course I've taken in my entire life. The speakers are just reading what was in the slide and no further information was given. I suggest you just gave the learners a handout or something and we will read it on our own. This course will never fail to disappoint learners, especially those who don't have background in Statistics.
column19:
1) We will appreciate it more if this course have better visual aids. I mean, yes there is a part in the lecture which narrates how to do ANOVA in Excel. My question is, why narrate it if you can demonstrate (via video) how to do it? Also, images and plots are so small and blurred that axes labels are almost unreadable.

2) Maybe you can elaborate more on other topics. We've seen a lot of plots, but it was not discussed how to construct them and how to use them. In this course, they are given to learners as constructed plots, without teaching the learners how to construct them, and most importantly, how to interpret them. For example, how do we know when to say that a residual plot is "well-behaved?" I'm not well-versed in Statistics so the "well-behaved" and "not well-behaved" residual plots both looks chaotic to me. Maybe you should have given us some pointers or guidelines how to interpret these graphs?

3) I truly believe that the guest speakers of this course are knowledgeable in Statistics. I hope they will use their knowledge in demonstrating examples (real world examples) instead of just reading what was written in the slides. I actually finished some video presentation WITHOUT playing the video. I just read the transcript on the side because THE CONTENT OF THE VIDEO AND THE TRANSCRIPT ARE THE SAME. Sometimes illustrations/graphs are provided but due to the quality of the illustration, ITS ALMOST USELESS.

4) I hope the team will create a prerequisite for this course maybe? I think this is the first course in Statistical Analysis here  but Oh boy, the lectures looked like it treated us like learners with Master's degree in Statistics, continuously giving out technical words which I heard here for the first time in my entire life, and no explanation or whatsoever was given to even define what does those technical statistical terms mean.

column18: Understanding the concept and purpose of Experimental Design. Experimental design  means creating a set of procedures to test a hypothesis and laying out a detailed experimental plan in advance of doing the experiment to obtain data that can be analyze to yield valid and objective conclusions. It is the most familiar type of research design in the field of science and some other fields and industries. A well-chosen experimental designs can maximize the amount of information that can be obtain for a given amount of experimental effort.

I have a few points that I want to improve in this course.

1. Topics. Although I had previous machine learning courses before, personally, I am still challenged with following the discussion per video. The topics seem to be compressed into couple of videos and they are highly technical, with less application/demonstration in Python. 

2. Library. The course used mglearn package a lot. mglearn is a helper package that is used for the book "Introduction to Machine Learning with Python". I don't think that this is practical because I think we would be using mostly sklearn in field. Although it's helpful in the sense of discussing the concepts, but I think we should have focused on using sklearn.

3. Applicability. As mentioned in item 1, many topics are highly technical. This is okay, but we should have had a live demo (similar to Data Engineering using SQL), and focusing on sklearn. This is would boost further confidence on coding in Python. I codes were presented without going through the steps, which would really be challenging, especially, the library which was highly used is not a common package. I think that we should have built the habit for the learners to rely on sklearn.

I think the course need much improvement: 
- Please have a pre-requisite before taking the course. I'm an advanced beginner in coding (python) and haven't done machine learning before. So i was excited about this course as i thought it will guide me. Unfortunately, this is for mid to advanced skilled students not for beginners. I'm very disappointed that it's not really well explained (compared to the previous class I took). It almost discourage me from completing the course - but i need to cos I'm a Sparta scholar. 
- I know machine learning is difficult. I hope the team behind this course consult a beginner (or someone with 0 idea about machine learning) so they were able to make appropriate content that is for beginner. It's always possible to divide this course into two if one course isn't enough to fully grasp the topic.

Overall, this is not for beginner.

column19:
A serious limitation of the course is that students can't proceed to the next peer-graded assessment if they haven't received a passing grade from the assessment of the previous week. It took around 4-6 weeks to get a grade for each assessment, even as I attempted to give the maximum possible number of assessments (around 12-16) to try and reduce the peer grading backlog. Please consider opening assessments so that students can proceed to the next week's assessment without having to wait for a grade from their previous week's assessment.

Video lectures are difficult to understand, especially for beginners. Most videos seem to be inadequate summaries of corresponding sections of the "Deep Learning with Python" by Fran?ois Chollet and are extremely difficult to learn from without consulting the source material. The videos should be recreated with more thorough explanation.

Assessments also involve only slight tweaks to the sample codes presented in lecture, so perhaps it would be better to include prompts that encourage exploration (e.g. have students try to identify why particular metrics change when varying specific hyperparameters).
